				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><p class=3D"mw-empty=
-elt">
</p><p>Depending on context (e.g. language, culture, region), some <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Large number">large numbers</a> have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Name" title=3D"Name">names</a> that allow for describing large quant=
ities in a textual form; not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathe=
matics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematical</a>. For very large values, the =
text is generally shorter than a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
ecimal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> numeric representation although longe=
r than <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation" title=
=3D"Scientific notation">scientific notation</a>.
</p><p>Two naming scales for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large=
_numbers" title=3D"Large numbers">large numbers</a> have been used in Engli=
sh and other European languages since the early modern era: the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_and_short_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Long and short scale">long and short scales</a>. Most English varia=
nts use the short scale today, but the long scale remains dominant in many =
non-English-speaking areas, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Continental_Europe" title=3D"Continental Europe">continental Europe</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_language" title=3D"Sp=
anish language">Spanish</a>-speaking countries in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/The_Americas" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"The Americas">=
the Americas</a>. These naming procedures are based on taking the number <i=
>n</i> occurring in 10<sup>3<i>n</i>+3</sup> (short scale) or 10<sup>6<i>n<=
/i></sup> (long scale) and concatenating Latin roots for its units, tens, a=
nd hundreds place, together with the suffix <i><span class=3D"nowrap">-illi=
on</span></i>.
</p><p>Names of numbers above a trillion are rarely used in practice; such =
large numbers have practical usage primarily in the scientific domain, wher=
e powers of ten are expressed as <i>10</i> with a numeric superscript. Howe=
ver, these somewhat rare names are considered acceptable for approximate st=
atements. For example, the statement "There are approximately 7.1&nbsp;octi=
llion atoms in an adult human body" is understood to be in short scale of t=
he table below (and is only accurate if referring to short scale rather tha=
n long scale).
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_numbering_system=
" title=3D"Indian numbering system">Indian numbering system</a> uses the na=
med numbers common between the long and short scales up to ten thousand. Fo=
r larger values, it includes named numbers at each multiple of 100; includi=
ng <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakh" title=3D"Lakh">lakh</a> (=
10<sup>5</sup>) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crore" title=
=3D"Crore">crore</a> (10<sup>7</sup>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-bellos_1-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numb=
ers#cite_note-bellos-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>English also has words, such as <i>zillion</i>, that are used inform=
ally to mean <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indefinite_and_fictit=
ious_numbers" title=3D"Indefinite and fictitious numbers">large but unspeci=
fied amounts</a>.
</p>
