<p>All of the dictionaries included <i>googol</i> and <i>googolplex</i>, ge=
nerally crediting it to the Kasner and Newman book and to Kasner's nephew (=
see below). None include any higher names in the googol family (googolduple=
x, etc.). The <i>Oxford English Dictionary</i> comments that <i>googol</i> =
and <i>googolplex</i> are "not in formal mathematical use".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Usage_of_names_of_large_num=
bers">Usage of names of large numbers</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DNames_of_large_numbers&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Usage of names of large numbers"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some names of large numbers, such as <i>million</i>, <i>billion</i>, and=
 <i>trillion</i>, have real referents in human experience, and are encounte=
red in many contexts, particularly in finance and economics. At times, the =
names of large numbers have been forced into common usage as a result of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperinflation" title=3D"Hyperinflat=
ion">hyperinflation</a>. The highest numerical value banknote ever printed =
was a note for 1&nbsp;sextillion <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
eng%C5%91" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Peng=C5=91">peng=C5=91</a> (10<su=
p>21</sup> or 1&nbsp;milliard bilpeng=C5=91 as printed) printed in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungary" title=3D"Hungary">Hungary</a> in=
 1946. In 2009, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zimbabwe" title=3D=
"Zimbabwe">Zimbabwe</a> printed a 100&nbsp;trillion (10<sup>14</sup>) <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zimbabwean_dollar" title=3D"Zimbabwean =
dollar">Zimbabwean dollar</a> note, which at the time of printing was worth=
 about US$30.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-zimbabwe_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-zimbabwe=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> In global economics, the name of a significantly larger nu=
mber was used in 2024, when the Russian news outlet <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/RBK_Group" title=3D"RBK Group">RBK</a> stated that the su=
m of legal claims against <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google" =
title=3D"Google">Google</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rus=
sia" title=3D"Russia">Russia</a> totalled 2&nbsp;undecillion (2<span style=
=3D"margin:0 .15em 0 .25em">=C3=97</span>10<sup><span class=3D"nowrap"><spa=
n data-sort-value=3D"7001360000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>36</span></sup>) =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_Ruble" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Russian Ruble">rubles</a>, or US$20&nbsp;decillion (US $2<span =
style=3D"margin:0 .15em 0 .25em">=C3=97</span>10<sup><span class=3D"nowrap"=
><span data-sort-value=3D"7001340000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>34</span></s=
up>); a value worth more than all financial assets in the world combined.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kremlin" title=3D"Kremlin">Kremlin</a> spokesperso=
n, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dmitry_Peskov" title=3D"Dmitry =
Peskov">Dmitry Peskov</a>, stated that this value was symbolic.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Na=
mes_of_large_numbers#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Names of larger numbers, however, have a tenuous, artificial existen=
ce, rarely found outside definitions, lists, and discussions of how large n=
umbers are named. Even well-established names like <i>sextillion</i> are ra=
rely used, since in the context of science, including astronomy, where such=
 large numbers often occur, they are nearly always written using <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation" title=3D"Scientific not=
ation">scientific notation</a>. In this notation, powers of ten are express=
ed as <i>10</i> with a numeric superscript, e.g. "The X-ray emission of the=
 radio galaxy is <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7045130000=
000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.3<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-righ=
t:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>45</sup>&nbsp;joules</span>." When a number =
such as 10<sup>45</sup> needs to be referred to in words, it is simply read=
 out as "ten to the forty-fifth" or "ten to the forty-five". This is easier=
 to say and less ambiguous than "quattuordecillion", which means something =
different in the long scale and the short scale.
</p><p>When a number represents a quantity rather than a count, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_prefix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI =
prefix">SI prefixes</a> can be used=E2=80=94thus "<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Femtosecond" title=3D"Femtosecond">femtosecond</a>", not "o=
ne quadrillionth of a second"=E2=80=94although often powers of ten are used=
 instead of some of the very high and very low prefixes. In some cases, spe=
cialized units are used, such as the astronomer's <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Parsec" title=3D"Parsec">parsec</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light_year" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Light year=
">light year</a> or the particle physicist's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Barn_(unit)" title=3D"Barn (unit)">barn</a>.
</p><p>Nevertheless, large numbers have an intellectual fascination and are=
 of mathematical interest, and giving them names is one way people try to c=
onceptualize and understand them.
</p><p>One of the earliest examples of this is <i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/The_Sand_Reckoner" title=3D"The Sand Reckoner">The Sand Rec=
koner</a></i>, in which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes=
" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> gave a system for naming large number=
s. To do this, he called the numbers up to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Myriad" title=3D"Myriad">myriad</a> myriad (10<sup>8</sup>) "fir=
st numbers" and called 10<sup>8</sup> itself the "unit of the second number=
s". Multiples of this unit then became the second numbers, up to this unit =
taken a myriad myriad times, 10<sup>8</sup>=C2=B710<sup>8</sup>=3D10<sup>16=
</sup>. This became the "unit of the third numbers", whose multiples were t=
