<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Origins_of_the_&quot;standa=
rd_dictionary_numbers&quot;"><span id=3D"Origins_of_the_.22standard_diction=
ary_numbers.22"></span>Origins of the "standard dictionary numbers"</h2><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNames_of_large_numb=
ers&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Origins of th=
e &quot;standard dictionary numbers&quot;"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Chuquet.gif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Chuquet.gif/5=
00px-Chuquet.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"500" height=3D"228" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"694" data-file-height=3D"317"></a><figc=
aption></figcaption></figure>
<p>The words <i>bymillion</i> and <i>trimillion</i> were first recorded in =
1475 in a manuscript of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jehan_Adam=
" title=3D"Jehan Adam">Jehan Adam</a>. Subsequently, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicolas_Chuquet" title=3D"Nicolas Chuquet">Nicolas Chuqu=
et</a> wrote a book <i>Triparty en la science des nombres</i> which was not=
 published during Chuquet's lifetime. However, most of it was copied by <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estienne_de_La_Roche" title=3D"Estien=
ne de La Roche">Estienne de La Roche</a> for a portion of his 1520 book, <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%27arismetique" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"L'arismetique">L'arismetique</a></i>. Chuquet's book contain=
s a passage in which he shows a large number marked off into groups of six =
digits, with the comment:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Ou qui veult le premier point peult signiffier million Le second point b=
yllion Le tiers point tryllion Le quart quadrillion Le cinq<sup>e</sup> quy=
llion Le six<sup>e</sup> sixlion Le sept.<sup>e</sup> septyllion Le huyt<su=
p>e</sup> ottyllion Le neuf<sup>e</sup> nonyllion et ainsi des ault'<sup>s<=
/sup> se plus oultre on vouloit preceder
</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>(Or if you prefer the first mark can signify million, the second mark by=
llion, the third mark tryllion, the fourth quadrillion, the fifth quyillion=
, the sixth sixlion, the seventh septyllion, the eighth ottyllion, the nint=
h nonyllion and so on with others as far as you wish to go).
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Adam and Chuquet used the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_=
and_short_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Long and short scale">long =
scale</a> of powers of a million; that is, Adam's <i>bymillion</i> (Chuquet=
's <i>byllion</i>) denoted 10<sup>12</sup>, and Adam's <i>trimillion</i> (C=
huquet's <i>tryllion</i>) denoted 10<sup>18</sup>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Googol_family">Googol famil=
y</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNames_of_l=
arge_numbers&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Goog=
ol family"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>The names <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Googol" title=3D"G=
oogol">googol</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Googo=
lplex" title=3D"Googolplex">googolplex</a></i> were invented by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Kasner" title=3D"Edward Kasner">Edward=
 Kasner</a>'s nephew Milton Sirotta and introduced in Kasner and Newman's 1=
940 book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_and_the_Im=
agination" title=3D"Mathematics and the Imagination">Mathematics and the Im=
agination</a></i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-kasner_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-kasner=
-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> in the following passage:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The name "googol" was invented by a =
child (Dr. Kasner's nine-year-old nephew) who was asked to think up a name =
for a very big number, namely 1 with one hundred zeroes after it. He was ve=
ry certain that this number was not infinite, and therefore equally certain=
 that it had to have a name. At the same time that he suggested "googol" he=
 gave a name for a still larger number: "googolplex". A googolplex is much =
larger than a googol, but is still finite, as the inventor of the name was =
quick to point out. It was first suggested that a googolplex should be 1, f=
ollowed by writing zeros until you got tired. This is a description of what=
 would happen if one tried to write a googolplex, but different people get =
tired at different times and it would never do to have <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primo_Carnera" title=3D"Primo Carnera">Carnera</a> a b=
etter mathematician than <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Ei=
nstein" title=3D"Albert Einstein">Dr. Einstein</a>, simply because he had m=
ore endurance. The googolplex is, then, a specific finite number, equal to =
1 with a googol zeros after it.</p></blockquote>
