</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Horton_Conway" title=3D"Jo=
hn Horton Conway">John Horton Conway</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Richard_K._Guy" title=3D"Richard K. Guy">Richard K. Guy</a><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-conway_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-conway-18"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  have=
 suggested that <i>N-plex</i> be used as a name for 10<sup><i>N</i></sup>. =
This gives rise to the name <i>googolplexplex</i> for 10<sup>googolplex</su=
p> =3D 10<sup>10<sup>10<sup>100</sup></sup></sup>. Conway and Guy<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-conway_18-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-conway-18"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> have propo=
sed that <i>N-minex</i> be used as a name for 10<sup>=E2=88=92<i>N</i></sup=
>, giving rise to the name <i>googolminex</i> for the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reciprocal_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Reciprocal (mathematics)">reciprocal</a> of a googolplex, which is writ=
ten as 10<sup>=E2=88=92(10<sup>100</sup>)</sup>. None of these names are in=
 wide use.
</p><p>A googologist from Texas coined the term giggol for a tetrational nu=
mber. Giggol is equal to <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-i=
nline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D=
"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle {10\uparrow \uparrow 100}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mn>10</mn>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=91<!-- =E2=86=91 -->=E2=86=91<!-- =
=E2=86=91 --></mo>
          <mn>100</mn>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {10\uparrow \=
uparrow 100}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4c96d454af941fb79983335b13721978f180d5b5" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:9.428ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {10=
\uparrow \uparrow 100}}"></span>, or 10 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Tetration" title=3D"Tetration">tetrated</a> to 100. If it is written =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Expone=
ntiation">exponentiation</a>, then it would be a power tower of 100 tens. I=
t was coined by altering the vowel sound of "googol".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_lar=
ge_numbers#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The names <i>googol</i> and <i>googolplex</i> inspired the name of t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot-com_company" title=3D"Dot-c=
om company">Internet company</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
oogle" title=3D"Google">Google</a> and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Corporate_headquarters" title=3D"Corporate headquarters">corporate=
 headquarters</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Googleplex"=
 title=3D"Googleplex">Googleplex</a>, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-goog=
le_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names=
_of_large_numbers#cite_note-google-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extensions_of_the_standard_=
dictionary_numbers">Extensions of the standard dictionary numbers</h2><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNames_of_large_number=
s&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Extensions of t=
he standard dictionary numbers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further info=
rmation: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billion" title=3D"Billion=
">billion</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_and_short_s=
cales" title=3D"Long and short scales">Long and short scales</a></div>
<p>This section illustrates several systems for naming large numbers, and s=
hows how they can be extended past <i>vigintillion</i>.
</p><p>Traditional British usage assigned new names for each power of one m=
illion (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_and_short_scale" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Long and short scale">long scale</a>): <span=
 class=3D"nowrap">1,000,000 =3D 1 million</span>; <span class=3D"nowrap">1,=
000,000<sup>2</sup> =3D 1 billion</span>; <span class=3D"nowrap">1,000,000<=
sup>3</sup> =3D 1 trillion</span>; and so on. It was adapted from French us=
age, and is similar to the system that was documented or invented by <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicolas_Chuquet" title=3D"Nicolas Chuque=
t">Chuquet</a>.
</p><p>Traditional American usage (which was also adapted from French usage=
 but at a later date), Canadian, and modern British usage assign new names =
for each power of one thousand (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Long_and_short_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Long and short scale=
">short scale</a>). Thus, a <i>billion</i> is <span class=3D"nowrap">1000 =
=C3=97 1000<sup>2</sup> =3D 10<sup>9</sup></span>; a <i>trillion</i> is <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap">1000 =C3=97 1000<sup>3</sup> =3D 10<sup>12</sup></span>=
; and so forth. Due to its dominance in the financial world (along with the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_dollar" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"US dollar">US dollar</a>), this was adopted for official <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Nations" title=3D"United Nations">=
United Nations</a> documents.
</p><p>Traditional French usage has varied; in 1948, France, which had orig=
inally popularized the short scale worldwide, reverted to the long scale.
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Petelier_long_scale"></span>
The term <i>milliard</i> is unambiguous and always means 10<sup>9</sup>. It=
 is seldom seen in American usage and rarely in British usage, but frequent=
ly in continental European usage. The term is sometimes attributed to Frenc=
h mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Peletier_d=
u_Mans" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Jacques Peletier du Mans">Jacques Pe=
letier du Mans</a> <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-spac=
e:nowrap;">=E2=80=891550</span> (for this reason, the long scale is also kn=
own as the <i>Chuquet-Peletier</i> system), but the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary" title=3D"Oxford English Dictio=
nary">Oxford English Dictionary</a> states that the term derives from post-=
Classical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"Latin">L=
atin</a> term <i>milliartum</i>, which became <i>milliare</i> and then <i>m=
illiart</i> and finally our modern term.
</p><p>Concerning names ending in -illiard for numbers 10<sup>6<i>n</i>+3</=
sup>, <i>milliard</i> is certainly in widespread use in languages other tha=
n English, but the degree of actual use of the larger terms is questionable=
. The terms "milliardo" in Italian, "Milliarde" in German, "miljard" in Dut=
ch, "milyar" in Turkish, and "=D0=BC=D0=B8=D0=BB=D0=BB=D0=B8=D0=B0=D1=80=D0=
=B4", <i>milliard</i> (transliterated) in Russian, are standard usage when =
discussing financial topics.
</p><p>The naming procedure for large numbers is based on taking the number=
 <i>n</i> occurring in 10<sup>3<i>n</i>+3</sup> (short scale) or 10<sup>6<i=
>n</i></sup> (long scale) and concatenating Latin roots for its units, tens=
, and hundreds place, together with the suffix <i><span class=3D"nowrap">-i=
llion</span></i>. In this way, numbers up to 10<sup>3=C2=B7999+3</sup>&nbsp=
;=3D&nbsp;10<sup>3000</sup> (short scale) or 10<sup>6=C2=B7999</sup>&nbsp;=
=3D&nbsp;10<sup>5994</sup> (long scale) may be named. The choice of roots a=
nd the concatenation procedure is that of the standard dictionary numbers i=
f <i>n</i> is 9 or smaller. For larger <i>n</i> (between 10 and 999), prefi=
xes can be constructed based on a system described by Conway and Guy.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-conway_18-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-conway-18"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Today,=
 sexdecillion and novemdecillion are standard dictionary numbers and, using=
 the same reasoning as Conway and Guy did for the numbers up to nonillion, =
could probably be used to form acceptable prefixes. The Conway=E2=80=93Guy =
system for forming prefixes:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-conway_18-3" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_=
note-conway-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"P=
age: 15">:=E2=80=8A15=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
