<p>The Conway=E2=80=93Guy system disagrees with some standard dictionary na=
mes, like "quindecillion", "sexdecillion", and "novemdecillion". Oliver Mia=
kinen argued that since "quindecillion" is a widely accepted term, and the =
Latin for 15 is actually <i>quindecim</i> and not <i>quinquadecim</i>, the =
prefix "quinqua-" should be replaced with "quin-". This new prefix is more =
commonly used nowadays.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-23"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>Since the system of using Latin prefixes will become ambiguous for n=
umbers with exponents of a size which the Romans rarely counted to, like 10=
<sup>6,000,258</sup>, Conway and Guy co-devised with Allan Wechsler the fol=
lowing set of consistent conventions that permit, in principle, the extensi=
on of this system indefinitely to provide English short-scale names for any=
 integer whatsoever.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-conway_18-4" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-con=
way-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> The name of a number 10<sup>3<i>n</i>+3</sup>, where <i=
>n</i> is greater than or equal to 1000, is formed by concatenating the nam=
es of the numbers of the form 10<sup>3<i>m</i>+3</sup>, where <i>m</i> repr=
esents each group of comma-separated digits of <i>n</i>, with each but the =
last "<span class=3D"nowrap">-illion</span>" trimmed to "<span class=3D"now=
rap">-illi-</span>", or, in the case of <i>m</i> =3D 0, either "-nilli-" or=
 "-nillion".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-conway_18-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Names_of_large_numbers#cite_note-conway-18">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> For example, 10<sup>3,000,012</sup>, the 1,000,003rd "<span cla=
ss=3D"nowrap">-illion</span>" number, equals one "millinillitrillion"; 10<s=
up>33,002,010,111</sup>, the 11,000,670,036th "<span class=3D"nowrap">-illi=
on</span>" number, equals one "undecillinilli=C2=ADseptua=C2=ADginta=C2=ADs=
es=C2=ADcentilli=C2=ADsestrigint=C2=ADillion"; and 10<sup>29,629,629,633</s=
up>, the 9,876,543,210th "<span class=3D"nowrap">-illion</span>" number, eq=
uals one "nonillise=C2=ADseptua=C2=ADginta=C2=ADoctingentillitres=C2=ADquad=
ra=C2=ADginta=C2=ADquingentillideciducent=C2=ADillion".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
conway_18-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
ames_of_large_numbers#cite_note-conway-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The following table shows number names generated by the system descr=
